[/asy]

solution:
[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F;

A = (2,3);
B = (7,8);
C = (-4,6);
D = (A + B)/2;
E = (B + C)/2;
F = (C + A)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(D--E--F--cycle);

label("$A(2,3)$", A, SE);
label("$B(7,8)$", B, NE);
label("$C(-4,6)$", C, SW);
label("$D$", D, N);
label("$E$", E, NE);
label("$F$", F, SW);
[/asy]

Let $D,$ $E,$ and $F$ be the midpoints of $\overline{AB},$ $\overline{BC},$ and $\overline{AC},$ respectively.  Then by the Midline Theorem, $DE \parallel AC,$ $EF \parallel AB,$ and $FD \parallel BC.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F;

A = (2,3);
B = (7,8);
C = (-4,6);
D = (A + B)/2;
E = (B + C)/2;
F = (C + A)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(D--E--F--cycle);
draw(A--E);
draw(B--F);

label("$A(2,3)$", A, SE);
label("$B(7,8)$", B, NE);
label("$C(-4,6)$", C, SW);
label("$D$", D, N);
label("$E$", E, NE);
label("$F$", F, SW);
[/asy]

Hence, $BD = FD = DE = EB = \frac{1}{2} AB,$ $EC = FC = FE = EA = \frac{1}{2} AC,$ and $AF = DF = FD = FA = \frac{1}{2} AC.$  Furthermore, $\angle AFD = \angle BFE = \angle EFD = 90^\circ.$  Hence, the area of $\triangle ABC$ is $4$ times the area of $\triangle DEF.$

By the Shoelace Theorem, the area of $\triangle DEF$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} |(2 + 3 + 0)(3 + 8 + 6) - (3 + 8 + 6)(2 + 0 + (-4))| = \boxed{\frac{39}{2}}.\]

original_solution:
First of all, let us draw one of these pieces in question, labeling points of interest as necessary: [asy]
