solution:
Let $ABCD$ be the quadrilateral, and let $E$ be the intersection of the diagonals.  Since $E$ is the midpoint of both $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{BD}$, $AE = EC = 15$ and $BE = ED = 10$.

[asy]
unitsize(6mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7pt)+fontsize(10pt));
dotfactor=3;

pair A=(10,0), B=(0,10), C=(-10,0), D=(0,-10);
pair Ep=(0,0);
pair[] dots={A,B,C,D,Ep};

draw(A--B--C--D--A);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);

dot(dots);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,E);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,W);
label("$E$",Ep,E);
[/asy]

Let $F$ and $G$ be the midpoints of $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{CD}$, respectively.  Then by the Midpoint Theorem, $FG$ is parallel to $AC$ and $FG = \frac{AC}{2} = 15$.  Also, $AG$ is parallel to $BC$ and $AG = \frac{BC}{2}$.

[asy]
unitsize(6mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7pt)+fontsize(10pt));
dotfactor=3;

pair A=(10,0), B=(0,10), C=(-10,0), D=(0,-10);
pair Ep=(0,0);
pair F=(A+B)/2, G=(C+D)/2;
pair[] dots={A,B,C,D,Ep,F,G};

draw(A--B--C--D--A);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(F--G);

dot(dots);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,E);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,W);
label("$E$",Ep,E);
label("$F$",F,NE);
label("$G$",G,SW);
[/asy]

Since $AC \perp BD$, $FG \perp BD$.  It follows that $\angle EGF = 90^\circ$.  Then by the Pythagorean Theorem, \begin{align*}
EG^2 &= EF^2 + FG^2\\
&= \left(\frac{AB}{2}\right)^2 + 15^2.
\end{align*}Similarly,  \begin{align*}
EG^2 &= EH^2 + HG^2\\
&= \left(\frac{CD}{2}\right)^2 + 15^2.
\end{align*}From these equations, $AB = CD$.  Hence, $ABCD$ is a kite, which is a special case of a convex quadrilateral with perpendicular diagonals.  The maximum area is therefore $\frac{1}{2}(20)(30) = \boxed{300}$ square units.

original_solution:
[asy]
pair P,Q,R;
P = (0,0);
Q = (3*sqrt(24),0);
R = (0,3);
draw(P--Q--R--P);
draw(rightanglemark(Q,P,R,18));
label("$P$",P,SW);
label("$Q$",Q,SE);
label("$R$",R,N);
label("$15$",(R+Q)/2,NE);
[/asy]

We have $\tan R = \frac{PQ}{PR}$ and $\cos Q = \frac{PQ}{QR} = \frac{PQ}{15}$, so $\tan R = 5\cos Q$ gives us $\frac{PQ}{PR} = 5\cdot \frac{PQ}{15} = \frac{PQ}{3}$.  From $\frac{PQ}{PR} = \frac{PQ}{3}$, we have $PR = 3$.  Finally, the Pythagorean Theorem gives us \begin{align*}
PQ & = \sqrt{QR^2 - PR^2} \\
&=\sqrt{15^2 - 3^2}\\
&=\sqrt{(5\cdot 3)^2 - 3^2} \\
&= \sqrt{25\cdot 3^2 - 3^2} \\
&= \sqrt{24\cdot 3^2} \\
&= \sqrt{6\cdot 4\cdot 3^2} \\
&= \boxed{6\sqrt{6}}.
\end{align*}

