We have $\cos Q = \frac{PQ}{QR} = \frac{PQ}{20}$, so $\sin Q = 5 \cos Q \tan R$ gives us $\sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{PQ}{20}\right)^2} = 5\left(\frac{PQ}{20}\right)\left(\frac{PR}{PQ}\right) = \frac{PR}{4}$.  Squaring both sides and rearranging, we get $PR = \sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{PQ}{20}\right)^2}$.  Finally, the Pythagorean Theorem gives us \begin{align*}
PR & = \sqrt{QR^2 - PQ^2} \\
&=\sqrt{20^2 - PQ^2}\\
&=\sqrt{(2\cdot 10)^2 - PQ^2} \\
&= \sqrt{4\cdot 100 - PQ^2} \\
&= \sqrt{2\cdot 200 - PQ^2} \\
&= \boxed{2\sqrt{49}}.
\end{align*}

original_solution:
This question has a sincere need for a diagram!

[asy]
size(200);
pair X=(1,0);
pair Y=dir(120)*(1,0);
pair Z=dir(-100)*(1,0);

real t =60;
pair B=dir(t)*(2.0,0);
pair A=dir(t+130)*(2.86,0);
pair C=dir(t+250)*(1.6,0);

draw(unitcircle);
draw(A--B--C--A);
draw(X--Y--Z--X);

label("$A$",A,W);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,SE);
label("$X$",X,E);
label("$Y$",Y,NW);
label("$Z$",Z,SW);

label("$40^\circ$",A+(.2,.06),E);
label("$60^\circ$",B-(0,.2),SW);
label("$80^\circ$",C+(0,.15),NW);
[/asy]

Since we are considering the incenter, $\triangle BYX$ is isosceles, and indeed is equilateral.  Therefore $\angle BYX=60^\circ$.  This tells us  \[180^\circ=\angle AYB=\angle AYX+\angle BYX=\angle AYX+60^\circ.\]Solving gives $\angle AYX=\boxed{120^\circ}$.

We begin by drawing a diagram:

[asy]
size(100);
pair A,B,C;
real x = sqrt(3);
C=(0,0); A=(10,0); B=(0,10*x);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(B,C,A,30));
label("$A$",A,SE); label("$C$",C,SW); label("$B$",B,NW); label("10",(A+C)/2,S);

real r = 5*sqrt(3) - 5;
draw(Circle((r,r),r));
[/asy]

Since $\angle A = 60^\circ$, we have $\angle B = 180^\circ - 90^\circ - 60^\circ = 30^\circ$.  Then $\triangle ABC$ is a $30 - 60 - 90$ triangle, so $BC=AC\sqrt{3}=10\sqrt{3}$ and $AB=2AC=20$.  We can compute the area of $\triangle ABC$ as \[ [\triangle ABC] = \frac{1}{2}(AC)(BC)=\frac{1}{2}(10)(10\sqrt{3}) = 50\sqrt{3}.\]Let the incircle of $\triangle ABC$ have radius $r$.  A triangle with inradius $r$ and semiperimeter $s$ has \[\text{area} = rs,\]so we have  \[ [\triangle ABC] = r \left( \frac{10+10\sqrt{3}+20}{2} \right) = r(15+5\sqrt{3}).\]Setting these two area expressions equal gives \[50\sqrt{3}=r(15+5\sqrt{3}).\]Solving for $r$ gives  \[r = \frac{10\sqrt{3}}{3+\sqrt{3}} = \frac{10\sqrt{3}(3-\sqrt{3})}{9-3} = \boxed{5(\sqrt{3}-1)}.\]

