We label the points as shown.  $C$ is the midpoint of $AB$, and $D$ is a vertex of the smaller triangle.  We look at 30-60-90 $\triangle ACD$.  We seek a ratio of areas, which remains constant no matter the side lengths, so for simplicity, we let the big triangle have side length $2$ and the small triangle have side length $2x$.  Then, $AC=1-x$, $CD=x$, and $AD$ is a radius of the circle, which has length $1$ by 30-60-90 triangles.  Then, the Pythagorean theorem states that $AC^2+CD^2=AD^2$, or \[(1-x)^2 + x^2 = 1^2.\]   Simplifying the equation yields \begin{align*}
& 1-2x+x^2 + x^2 = 1 \\
\Longleftrightarrow\ & 2x^2 - 2x=0 \\
\Longleftrightarrow\ & 2x(x-1)=0.
\end{align*} Thus, $x=0$ or $x=1$.  Clearly, $x\ne 0$, so $x=1$ is the only solution.  Then the small triangle has side length $2x=2$, and area equal to that of the large triangle, so the small triangle has \[\frac{2^2}{2^2}=\boxed{100\%}\] the area of the large triangle.

