problem:
Points $A$, $B$, $C$ and $D$ are on a circle such that $AB = 10$ and $CD = 20.$ Points $W$, $X$, $Y$, and $Z$ are on a circle such that $\overline{YW}$ and $\overline{XZ}$ are diameters, and $WY = 20.$ The scale factor of $\triangle ABC$ to $\triangle XYZ$ is $2.$ If $m\angle A = m\angle X$, what is the number of possible values of $m\angle Z$?

[asy]
size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
pair A=3dir(110), B=3dir(160), C=3dir(270), D=3dir(330), W=2dir(45), X=2dir(225), Y=2dir(315), Z=2dir(135);
draw(unitcircle);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--cycle);
draw(B--W);
draw(C--X);
draw(D--Z);
draw(A--D);
draw(B--Y);
draw(C--Z);
draw(D--W);
draw(Circle(D,3), dashed);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,SE);
label("$W$",W,NE);
label("$X$",X,SW);
label("$Y$",Y,SE);
label("$Z$",Z,NW);
[/asy]

solution:
Notice that $\triangle ABC \sim \triangle XYZ$ with a scale factor of 2.  Therefore, $\angle C = \angle Z$ and $XY = 5.$

Because $WY = 20,$ the radius of the circle containing $\triangle XYZ$ is $10,$ so the length of its diameter is $20.$

[asy]
size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
pair A=3dir(110), B=3dir(160), C=3dir(270), D=3dir(330), W=2dir(45), X=2dir(225), Y=2dir(315), Z=2dir(135);
draw(unitcircle);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--cycle);
draw(B--W);
draw(C--X);
draw(D--Z);
draw(A--D);
draw(B--Y);
draw(C--Z);
draw(D--W);
draw(Circle(D,3), dashed);
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,SE);
label("$W$",W,NE);
label("$X$",X,SW);
label("$Y$",Y,SE);
label("$Z$",Z,NW);
[/asy]

Because $\angle C = \angle Z,$ quadrilateral $BCZW$ is cyclic.  Because $\overline{WY}$ is the diameter of the circle, $\angle ZYW = 90^\circ,$ so $\angle ZBW = 90^\circ.$  Also, $\angle WCZ = \angle ZBW,$ so $\angle WCZ = 90^\circ.$  Since $C$ lies on the circle that contains $Z,$ we can let $D$ be the other intersection point of $\overline{WC}$ and the circle.

[asy]
size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
pair A=3dir(110), B=3dir(160), C=3dir(270), D=3dir(330), W=2dir(45), X=2dir(225), Y=2dir(315), Z=2dir(135);
draw(unitcircle);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--cycle);
draw(B--W);
draw(C--X);
draw(D--Z);
draw(A--D);
draw(B--Y);
draw(C--Z);
draw(D--W);
draw(Circle(D,3), linetype("4 4"));
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,NE);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("$D$",D,SE);
label("$W$",W,NE);
label("$X$",X,SW);
label("$Y$",Y,SE);
label("$Z$",Z,NW);
[/asy]

Since $D$ lies on $\overline{WC},$ $C$ lies on $\overline{ZW},$ and $W$ lies on $\overline{ZY},$ $\angle ZWC = \angle ZDC$ and $\angle ZYW = \angle ZWC.$  Since $\angle ZYW = 90^\circ,$ $\angle ZWC = \angle ZDC = 90^\circ,$ so quadrilateral $DCZB$ is cyclic.

We see that $\angle A = \angle X$ and $\angle C = \angle Z,$ so $\angle B = \angle Y.$  Since $AB = 10$ and $XY = 5,$ $D$ must be the circumcircle of $\triangle ABC.$

Since $W$ and $Y$ are on the circumcircle of $\triangle ABC,$ $\angle AWB = \angle AYB.$  Also, $\angle AYB = \angle AWB = 90^\circ$ (since $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{XY}$ are chords of circles with diameter $\overline{WY}$ and $\overline{ZW}$ respectively).  Since $A$ and $Y$ are 10 units from $B,$ $A$ and $Y$ must coincide.  Hence, there is only $\boxed{1}$ possible value of $m\angle Z.$

