Since $\angle BMC = \angle CMD = 90^\circ$, we have $\angle BMA = 180^\circ - \angle BMC - \angle CMD = 44^\circ$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,0);
B = dir(46);
D = dir(-46);
C = 2*dir(0);
M = B + D;

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(B--M--D);
draw(rightanglemark(B,M,D,10));
draw(rightanglemark(A,B,M,10));
draw(rightanglemark(A,D,M,10));
draw(B--D,dashed);
draw(A--M,red,Arrow(6));

label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, NW);
label("$C$", C, E);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$M$", M, N);
label("$1$", (A + B)/2, NW);
label("$1$", (A + D)/2, SW);
label("$1$", (B + M)/2, N);
label("$1$", (M + D)/2, NE);
label("$44^\circ$", A, NE);
[/asy]

Let $AM = x$.  Then $\tan \angle BAM = \frac{BM}{AM} = \frac{1}{x}$ and $\tan \angle DAM = \frac{DM}{AM} = \frac{1}{x}$, so $\tan \angle BAD = \tan (\angle BAM + \angle DAM) = \frac{\frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{x}}{1 - (\frac{1}{x})(\frac{1}{x})} = \frac{\frac{2}{x}}{1 - \frac{1}{x^2}} = \frac{2x}{x^2 - 1} = \tan 46^\circ$.  Solving for $x$, we find $x = \boxed{1 + \sqrt{2}}$.

original_problem:
In triangle $ABC$, $AB = 11$, $AC = 13$, and $BC = 20$.  The medians $AD$, $BE$, and $CF$ of triangle $ABC$ intersect at the centroid $G$.  Let $P$ be the foot of the altitude from $G$ to $BC$.  Find $GP$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, G, P;

A = (44/5,33/5);
B = (0,0);
C = (20,0);
D = (B + C)/2;
E = (C + A)/2;
F = (A + B)/2;
G = (A + B + C)/3;
P = (G + reflect(B,C)*(G))/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(B--E);
draw(C--F);
draw(G--P);

label("$A$", A, dir(90));
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$E$", E, NE);
label("$F$", F, NW);
label("$G$", G, NE);
label("$P$", P, SSW);
[/asy]

original_solution:
Let $Q$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $BC$.  Then triangles $AQD$ and $GPD$ are similar.  Furthermore, \[\frac{GP}{AQ} = \frac{GD}{AD} = \frac{1}{3},\]so to find $GP$, we can find $AQ$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, G, P, Q;

A = (44/5,33/5);
B = (0,0);
C = (20,0);
D = (B + C)/2;
E = (C + A)/2;
F = (A + B)/2;
G = (A + B + C)/3;
P = (G + reflect(B,C)*(G))/2;
Q = (A + reflect(B,C)*(A))/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(B--E);
draw(C--F);
draw(G--P);
draw(A--Q);

label("$A$", A, dir(90));
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$E$", E, NE);
label("$F$", F, NW);
label("$G$", G, NE);
label("$P$", P, S);
label("$Q$", Q, SSW);
[/asy]

The semi-perimeter of the triangle is $(11 + 13 + 20)/2 = 22$, so by Heron's formula, the area of triangle $ABC$ is $$\sqrt{22(22 - 11)(22 - 13)(22 - 20)} = 66.$$Hence, the height of triangle $ABC$ with respect to base $BC$ is $AQ = 2 \cdot 66/BC = 2 \cdot 66/20 = 33/5$.  Therefore, $GP = AQ/3 = (33/5)/3 = \boxed{\frac{11}{5}}$.

